    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-01-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-01-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="257"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d257">
                <head>No. 970.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Child</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Bangkok</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-01-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">January</hi> 6, 1888</date>. (Received February
                        20.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 56.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inclose you the amended
                    liquor law of Siam, whereby the United States is included among the “most
                    favored nations.”<note n="*" xml:id="d257fn1">See <ref target="frus1887#pg_974"
                            >For. Rels., 1887, p. 974</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The omission was an oversight on the part of the translator, but so far the law
                    has remained inoperative.</p>
                <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Jacob T. Child.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
